## Explanation of Bug
The main issue is that `digits[n]` tries to access an element beyond the array bounds since valid indices are from 0 to n-1. This leads to undefined behavior and likely a runtime error.

Additionally, there's a logical flaw in how carry propagation is handled:
1. The code increments `digits[n]` (which is out of bounds) instead of just incrementing the last digit.
2. It doesn't properly handle the case where we need to add a new most significant digit when all digits are 9.

## Corrected Code
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> plusOne(vector<int>& digits) {
        int n = digits.size();

        // Start from the last digit and work backwards
        for (int i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            if (digits[i] < 9) {
                digits[i]++;
                return digits;
            }
            digits[i] = 0;
        }

        // If we reach here, all digits were 9, so we need to add a new digit
        digits.insert(digits.begin(), 1);
        return digits;
    }
};
```

## Explanation of Fix

The corrected approach:
1. **Proper indexing**: Uses `digits[n-1]` instead of `digits[n]`
2. **Efficient carry handling**: Processes from right to left, stopping as soon as a digit < 9 is found
3. **Clean logic**: Sets all processed digits to 0 and increments the first non-9 digit
4. **Handles edge case**: Creates new most significant digit when needed

This solution has O(n) time complexity and handles all edge cases correctly.

## Alternative Solution (More Explicit)
```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> plusOne(vector<int>& digits) {
        int n = digits.size();

        // Increment the last digit
        digits[n-1]++;

        // Handle carry from right to left
        for (int i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) {
            if (digits[i] > 9) {
                digits[i] = 0;
                digits[i-1]++;
            } else {
                break; // No more carry needed
            }
        }

        // Handle the case where first digit overflows
        if (digits[0] > 9) {
            digits[0] = 0;
            digits.insert(digits.begin(), 1);
        }

        return digits;
    }
};
```

The key insight is to process from right to left and handle carries efficiently, rather than trying to increment the "end" of an array that doesn't exist.

